widgets_values: We can save tiles more efficiently in a packed format. Look at the supplemental to see how tiles are arranged into a packing.
Here is a preview of the boundary conditions used to guide the inpainter to create tillable tiles
We can make a large random tiling! This node accepts the packed image, the individual tiles given by the "Tile Images" node, or the raw uncropped output of the inpainting process.
In this case we keep the top 50% of generated tiles.
This is a tiling where every tile tiles with every other tile, created by setting "colors=1". It tends to look much less diverse, but can be very robust.
You can instead separate tiles out into individual images.
A full set of dual tiles includes both interior and cross tiles.

This is the model and prompt to use for inpainting. I have found that SD2 works the best for challenging inpainting problems like this, but you can replace it any inpainting setup (standard model, finetuned model, controlnet) supported by ComfyUI.
Large tileset generation can result in batch sizes in the hundreds. This prevents OOM errors.

Even with good prompting, the inpainter sometimes makes garbage. We can create multiple candidates for each tile in the "Random Wang Boundaries" node and then pick the best ones here. This node does nothing if "canidates=1".

Setup the tile boundaries for inpainting! "ortho constrained" mode works best with textures that have long linear elements like boards. "arbitrary" mode works better on irregular textures. The tile resolution depends on the inpainting model being used: SD2 requires 256 and SDXL requires 512.

The dual tiling is generally the best looking, because it does not suffer from mismatched corners. But it is also farthest from the input image, has round-tripped through the VAE the most times, etc. This can cause its own problems.
